WEBVTT

00:07.007 --> 00:09.218
So, you want to be a secretary
for a talent manager.

00:09.218 --> 00:11.762
- Yes. Very much.
- Great.

00:12.763 --> 00:14.765
You're up.

00:14.849 --> 00:16.726
- Excuse me?
- Go ahead. I'm all ears.

00:16.726 --> 00:19.729
Oh. Well,
what would you like to know?

00:20.813 --> 00:22.732
Give me a minute.

00:28.988 --> 00:32.450
Do you have a natural flair
for meticulous organization?

00:32.450 --> 00:33.868
I'd say yes. Yes, I do.

00:33.868 --> 00:35.953
Great.

00:38.914 --> 00:40.916
You excuse me again?

00:46.881 --> 00:49.800
Can you always be depended upon
to do what you say you'll do?

00:49.884 --> 00:52.052
- Yes, certainly.
- Fantastic.

00:54.096 --> 00:55.848
Perhaps you'd like
to see my résumé?

00:55.848 --> 00:58.476
Excellent, yes,
let's take a gander.

00:58.476 --> 01:00.478
Three pages, huh?

01:00.478 --> 01:01.645
Mm-hmm.

01:01.729 --> 01:04.064
Come on. Some of this is
bullshit, right?

01:04.148 --> 01:05.483
Then I went
to Brooklyn College,

01:05.483 --> 01:06.942
where I got my B.A.
in English literature.

01:07.026 --> 01:08.611
Very good.

01:08.611 --> 01:11.530
And... why do you want
to work here?

01:11.614 --> 01:13.491
Many reasons. But first
and foremost, I'm excited

01:13.616 --> 01:15.367
to get in on the ground floor
of a growing business.

01:15.451 --> 01:16.911
Growing business.

01:16.911 --> 01:19.914
Okay, that's putting
a shit-ton of pressure on me.

01:19.914 --> 01:22.082
Do you have any questions
you'd like to ask me?

01:22.166 --> 01:24.627
Um, what will
a typical workday look like?

01:24.627 --> 01:28.088
Will you excuse me a minute?

01:29.089 --> 01:30.591
Every one of these broads,
they can type,

01:30.591 --> 01:33.844
they graduated from someplace,
they sit nice.

01:33.928 --> 01:36.388
I got this book with questions
to ask. It's no fucking help.

01:36.472 --> 01:37.973
All the girls give
the same answer,

01:38.057 --> 01:39.934
because they all probably got
a fucking book, too.

01:39.934 --> 01:41.393
You ever hire anybody?

01:41.477 --> 01:42.728
Sure, lots of people. <i>- Well, what kind of stuff</i>

01:42.812 --> 01:44.021
<i>do you ask,
so you know who to pick?</i>

01:44.021 --> 01:45.940
That depends.
You got to tailor the questions

01:45.940 --> 01:47.107
to the specific job.

01:47.191 --> 01:48.400
Yeah. How, Fred? How?

01:48.484 --> 01:50.402
Well, when I hired a guy
to paint my apartment,

01:50.486 --> 01:52.655
I asked if he had a ten-foot ladder. <i>- Okay.</i>

01:52.655 --> 01:54.949
But I didn't ask that
when I hired my tax guy

01:54.949 --> 01:57.201
<i>or the girl to get my brother
laid after his divorce.</i>

01:57.201 --> 01:58.869
<i>You don't need a ladder
for those jobs.</i>

01:58.953 --> 02:01.497
Fred, did you ever hire anybody
at William Morris

02:01.497 --> 02:03.916
in a professional,
show-business capacity?

02:03.916 --> 02:05.000
Not per se.

02:05.084 --> 02:06.252
I'm hanging up. <i>- Wait.</i>

02:06.252 --> 02:08.546
You should definitely see
how the person chews.

02:08.546 --> 02:10.172
<i>- What?</i>
- I'm serious.

02:10.256 --> 02:12.132
You're going to be in
close quarters with this girl,

02:12.216 --> 02:15.052
with snacks and whatnot,
munching and crunching,

02:15.052 --> 02:16.262
<i>day in, day out.</i>

02:16.262 --> 02:19.014
<i>If they chew loud,
you're doomed.</i>

02:19.098 --> 02:21.141
My shorthand is excellent,
and I type 70 words per minute.

02:21.225 --> 02:23.185
- Mm-hmm.
- I'm friendly but I'm firm.

02:23.269 --> 02:25.229
Your time is precious,
and I'll be the gatekeeper.

02:25.229 --> 02:27.273
There will be
no unwarranted interruptions.

02:27.273 --> 02:28.899
Yes, that is all
very interesting.

02:28.983 --> 02:30.359
Very interesting.

02:30.359 --> 02:32.319
Hey, you hungry?

02:32.403 --> 02:34.613
- Uh, no, not really.
- 'Cause I was about to eat this, but now...

02:34.697 --> 02:35.865
why don't you have it?

02:35.865 --> 02:37.449
Thank you, no, I just had lunch.

02:37.533 --> 02:38.909
I'll cut it up for you.
I got a pocketknife.

02:38.993 --> 02:40.244
That's very nice,
but really, no.

02:40.244 --> 02:41.620
Oh, come on,
it's nice and crispy.

02:41.704 --> 02:43.163
To be honest,
I'm actually allergic...

02:43.247 --> 02:44.748
Eat the fucking apple!

03:09.273 --> 03:10.983
- Papa, are you up?
- Who is it?

03:10.983 --> 03:12.318
It's me, Abe.

03:12.318 --> 03:14.153
It's not you.

03:14.153 --> 03:17.698
- Stop that, please.
- It's not me.

03:17.698 --> 03:19.074
Did I wake you?

03:19.158 --> 03:20.951
Sorry,
I figured you'd be reading.

03:21.035 --> 03:22.953
Your mother made me
turn out my light.

03:23.037 --> 03:24.371
Now, what is it?

03:24.455 --> 03:26.457
I need some help,
but I'll ask you tomorrow.

03:26.457 --> 03:28.083
No, it's fine.
I was just lying there

03:28.167 --> 03:30.127
thinking about how she made me
turn out my light.

03:30.127 --> 03:32.171
I just can't get my checkbook
to balance,

03:32.171 --> 03:34.423
- and it's driving me crazy.
- What's going on?

03:34.423 --> 03:36.175
Nothing. Miriam can't balance
her checkbook.

03:36.175 --> 03:38.135
Why on earth
would you have her doing that

03:38.135 --> 03:40.512
- in the middle of the night, Abe?
- I live in a Dr. Seuss book.

03:40.596 --> 03:42.348
I'm sorry I got you up.
Back to bed, you two.

03:42.348 --> 03:44.433
- Night night.
- I can't sleep when your father's just lying there

03:44.433 --> 03:46.393
thinking about how I made him
turn out the light.

03:46.477 --> 03:48.687
- Then let me turn on my light.
- Fine, I'll sleep on the couch.

03:48.771 --> 03:51.148
Do not sleep on the couch.
It wears out the cushions faster

03:51.148 --> 03:55.319
- than just everyday sitting.
- Then I'm going back to bed.

03:55.319 --> 03:57.279
Where's the checkbook?

03:57.363 --> 03:58.822
In the kitchen.

03:58.906 --> 04:00.866
It's been weeks.
You have to stop fighting.

04:00.950 --> 04:02.826
Who's fighting?
I'm simply recalibrating

04:02.910 --> 04:04.912
my entire relationship
with your mother

04:04.912 --> 04:07.164
based on information she
previously chose to keep secret

04:07.164 --> 04:08.582
for 35 years.

04:08.666 --> 04:11.210
Okay. Could you stop that, then?

04:11.210 --> 04:13.212
It comes out different
every time.

04:13.212 --> 04:15.673
- Always terrible but never the same.
- Ugh.

04:16.757 --> 04:18.133
What's this?

04:18.217 --> 04:20.177
Is it better if it's a one
or a seven?

04:20.177 --> 04:22.054
It's less bad if it's a seven.

04:22.054 --> 04:23.722
Call it a seven.

04:23.806 --> 04:25.766
And this is
what you're getting paid

04:25.766 --> 04:27.893
for selling
all that Tupperware?

04:27.977 --> 04:30.270
It's no way to get rich,
but I did win an aquarium.

04:30.354 --> 04:33.065
Which has been surprisingly
expensive to maintain.

04:33.065 --> 04:36.276
I sold the most pastel
Wonderliers in my region.

04:36.360 --> 04:39.446
- Mm-hmm.
- I also won those toasters and a salad spinner.

04:39.530 --> 04:41.365
And surely you've seen
the two large dalmatians

04:41.365 --> 04:42.866
in our living room.

04:42.908 --> 04:46.996
Do you think Joel could try
to contribute a little more?

04:46.996 --> 04:49.456
He's doing
everything he can, Papa.

04:49.540 --> 04:50.708
Well...

04:51.792 --> 04:53.627
There's your balance.

04:53.711 --> 04:56.046
Uh, that's if the number was
a seven.

04:56.130 --> 04:58.632
And that's if it was a one.

04:58.716 --> 05:01.218
I think even Ethan
could have helped you.

05:01.218 --> 05:05.055
Thanks, Papa. Really.

05:05.139 --> 05:07.725
Could I bring my book in here
and read?

05:07.725 --> 05:09.476
Sure.

05:09.560 --> 05:12.104
I'll forgive your mother
in the morning.

05:12.104 --> 05:14.982
For God's sake, the woman owns
a Chanel sleep mask.

05:29.371 --> 05:31.290
Looks like it's gonna be
four debates.

05:31.290 --> 05:32.708
Kennedy-Nixon?

05:32.708 --> 05:34.251
- He's such a creep.
- Which one?

05:34.251 --> 05:36.295
Nixon. Mei.

05:36.295 --> 05:37.629
They both have skeletons.

05:37.713 --> 05:38.797
You are not voting for Nixon.

05:38.881 --> 05:40.507
I am not voting for Nixon.

05:40.591 --> 05:41.884
He looks like he eats children.

05:41.884 --> 05:43.093
Thank you.

05:43.177 --> 05:44.386
Ethan wants

05:44.470 --> 05:46.221
one of these
Etch A Sketch things,

05:46.305 --> 05:48.682
but they're $2.99, and he'll
break it in, like, a day.

05:48.766 --> 05:50.184
What's an Etch A Sketch?

05:50.184 --> 05:51.935
You draw on the screen with the knobs,

05:52.019 --> 05:54.897
- then you shake it, and the picture erases.
- What's the point of that?

05:54.897 --> 05:57.608
To teach kids that nothing lasts.

05:57.608 --> 05:58.942
- Joel!
- What?

05:59.026 --> 06:00.611
You're not even gonna answer
the door?

06:00.611 --> 06:02.071
- Nah.
- Come on!

06:02.071 --> 06:03.697
We discussed this.

06:03.781 --> 06:05.574
It could be another one
of Ma's girls.

06:05.574 --> 06:08.660
- If I open it, I'm as good as engaged.
- It could be a delivery.

06:08.744 --> 06:10.037
- They'll leave it.
- Someone could steal it.

06:10.037 --> 06:11.288
Nothing lasts.

06:11.288 --> 06:12.289
What do you do at the club?

06:12.289 --> 06:13.457
- Shh.
- Why?

06:13.457 --> 06:15.084
In case they're listening
at the door.

06:15.084 --> 06:17.294
If the phone rings at the club,
you have to answer it.

06:17.294 --> 06:19.338
People want to come in,
you have to let them in.

06:19.338 --> 06:21.423
There's a protocol for women
of childbearing age.

06:21.507 --> 06:23.634
If they want to talk to me,
Mrs. Moskowitz screens them

06:23.634 --> 06:25.219
with a series
of discreet questions.

06:25.219 --> 06:27.221
- Oh, my God.
- The system's worked for weeks.

06:27.221 --> 06:29.264
- Why question it now?
- Because it's demented.

06:29.348 --> 06:30.891
Because it's...

06:30.891 --> 06:32.601
Aah! I'll do it!

06:32.601 --> 06:34.269
- Do what?
- I'll meet your parents.

06:34.353 --> 06:35.479
Just answer the phone!

06:35.479 --> 06:37.940
- No. We can wait my mother out.
- We can't.

06:37.940 --> 06:40.359
We can. She's getting older.
She has limited wind.

06:40.359 --> 06:41.860
We need our lives back, Joel.

06:41.944 --> 06:43.904
- My life is fine.
- Well, mine isn't.

06:43.904 --> 06:45.489
This is dumb.
I mean, you said it.

06:45.489 --> 06:48.033
We're in a... a...

06:48.117 --> 06:49.868
Relationship.

06:49.952 --> 06:51.245
Yes. That. Sure.

06:51.245 --> 06:52.663
They have to know.

06:52.663 --> 06:55.749
Make a date. End the madness.

06:55.833 --> 06:56.917
I'll just move again.

06:56.917 --> 06:58.752
A moving target
will confuse her.

07:03.173 --> 07:05.092
Set it up. Today.

07:05.092 --> 07:07.136
I'll be at the movies.

07:10.472 --> 07:12.099
Just in case.

07:18.397 --> 07:20.232
Susie? Oh. Sorry.

07:20.232 --> 07:22.109
I just need to talk to you
when you're done.

07:22.109 --> 07:23.902
- No, now's a good time.
- Should I wait outside?

07:23.986 --> 07:25.529
Nah. You ain't getting the job.

07:25.529 --> 07:27.865
- Oh. Okay, thank you.
- No. Thank you.

07:28.991 --> 07:31.660
- What's with your phone?
- Nothing. Why?

07:31.660 --> 07:34.705
- I've been calling all morning. All you get is a busy signal.
- Shit.

07:34.705 --> 07:36.915
You need a secretary.

07:36.999 --> 07:38.083
What do you think that was?

07:38.167 --> 07:39.877
What's up?

07:39.877 --> 07:41.587
- This.
- What is that?

07:41.587 --> 07:45.382
This is my invitation
to Shy Baldwin's wedding.

07:45.382 --> 07:46.967
Why the fuck
would you be invited

07:46.967 --> 07:49.094
- to Shy Baldwin's wedding?
- You tell me.

07:49.178 --> 07:50.971
I don't know.
They're working off an old list?

07:50.971 --> 07:54.391
- Then you would've been invited.
- And I was not invited.

07:54.391 --> 07:57.019
- Susie.
- I guess I was invited.

07:57.019 --> 07:59.271
Why the hell was I invited
to Shy Baldwin's wedding?

07:59.271 --> 08:01.315
And it's three days from now.

08:01.315 --> 08:02.900
Basic wedding etiquette dictates
invitations go out

08:02.900 --> 08:05.068
45 days prior to the event,
at a minimum.

08:05.152 --> 08:06.486
I'm sorry, you're offended
that you were invited

08:06.570 --> 08:08.697
at the last minute to a
wedding you don't want to go to?

08:08.697 --> 08:09.698
Yes. Who wouldn't be?

08:09.698 --> 08:11.450
- Me.
- And not only am I not going,

08:11.450 --> 08:13.243
I'm RSVPing "yes"
and then not going,

08:13.327 --> 08:14.703
just to screw up his count.

08:14.703 --> 08:15.996
You're a monster.

08:15.996 --> 08:18.165
That thing's a waste
of a nice gilded edge.

08:18.165 --> 08:20.709
You know what?
Maybe we should go.

08:20.709 --> 08:23.712
- Go? Are you kidding me?
- There's no way

08:23.712 --> 08:25.505
there's not an open bar,
some good food.

08:25.589 --> 08:26.924
You are not serious.

08:26.924 --> 08:28.217
He kind of owes us, you know?

08:28.217 --> 08:29.426
You could get
your picture taken there,

08:29.426 --> 08:31.803
get some good exposure
and some good cake.

08:31.887 --> 08:34.556
I am kind of curious to see
the whole spectacle.

08:34.640 --> 08:37.559
And I am really curious
to drink a lot of free booze.

08:39.603 --> 08:40.812
Did you see that?

08:40.896 --> 08:42.481
- See what?
- So you didn't?
- The smoke?

08:42.481 --> 08:44.233
- So you did.
- I did.

08:44.233 --> 08:46.235
- Damn. Damn it.
- Were we not supposed to?

08:46.235 --> 08:48.320
Of course you were,
but not then. Later.

08:49.780 --> 08:50.989
It's no good! I can't...

08:51.073 --> 08:52.532
What was I...
How am I supposed...

08:52.616 --> 08:54.076
Breathe it out.

08:54.076 --> 08:56.954
It was on four, not three.
Just have to remember to count.

08:56.954 --> 08:59.331
I'll just try it again.

09:03.585 --> 09:05.462
I'm looking pretty good to you
right now, aren't I?

09:08.507 --> 09:12.427
I got a net.
I should save for Ethan?

09:12.511 --> 09:14.179
We have saying back home:

09:14.263 --> 09:17.724
"Never too early for child
to learn how to bury."

09:17.808 --> 09:21.812
Mm. Let's just flush him and let
his memory be a blessing.

09:21.812 --> 09:24.439
Do we have any matches, Zelda?
This is dangerous.

09:24.523 --> 09:27.567
I saw Miss Miriam has matches
in her bedroom. I'll get them.

09:28.694 --> 09:30.988
I'll get it, Zelda.

09:34.324 --> 09:36.493
Weissman residence.

09:36.618 --> 09:38.620
Mm, this is she.

09:41.665 --> 09:43.125
Well, of course.

09:43.125 --> 09:45.502
I'd be very happy to meet
with Mr. Melamid.

09:46.545 --> 09:49.298
Certainly, any time he'd like.

09:49.298 --> 09:51.591
Today's fine.

09:51.675 --> 09:54.469
Half an hour.
I can be ready by then.

09:54.553 --> 09:57.347
It's 385 Riverside Drive
in Manhattan.

09:57.431 --> 09:58.640
Thank you so much.

09:58.724 --> 10:00.517
You're welcome. Thank you.

10:00.517 --> 10:01.977
<i>Goodbye.</i>

10:04.271 --> 10:06.690
As it turns out, I don't have
time for tea after all.

10:06.690 --> 10:08.608
There's a car coming for me.

10:08.692 --> 10:10.610
I have business in Scarsdale.

10:10.694 --> 10:12.946
Please tell Mr. Weissman
when he comes home.

10:13.030 --> 10:16.658
Okay, I'll tell him you went
outside to do your business.

10:17.743 --> 10:19.828
I'll just leave a note.

10:21.747 --> 10:25.375
<i>Holding hands at midnight ♪</i>

10:25.459 --> 10:29.046
<i>'Neath the starry sky ♪</i>

10:30.464 --> 10:33.258
<i>Nice work if you can get ♪</i>

10:33.342 --> 10:35.010
<i>And you can get it ♪</i>

10:35.010 --> 10:36.553
<i>If you try ♪</i>

10:36.553 --> 10:38.430
- Just over there, ma'am.
- Thank you.

10:38.430 --> 10:40.098
<i>♪ Strolling with...</i>

10:40.182 --> 10:41.933
Mrs. Weissman.

10:42.017 --> 10:44.311
Solomon Melamid.

10:44.311 --> 10:46.396
I'd, uh, shake your hand,
but mine is...

10:46.480 --> 10:48.690
straight from the horse's mouth, shall we say.

10:48.774 --> 10:50.359
- Anyway, welcome.
- Rose Weissman.

10:50.359 --> 10:51.735
It's a pleasure.

10:51.735 --> 10:53.278
Cut it out, Zephaniah.

10:53.362 --> 10:54.905
Don't let him scare you.

10:54.905 --> 10:57.115
Oh, it takes more than
a little showing off to do that.

10:57.199 --> 10:59.701
I grew up with horses.
In Oklahoma.

10:59.785 --> 11:01.953
- And I see you wore sensible shoes.
- Well, there's nothing elegant

11:02.037 --> 11:04.456
about landing on your backside
in the mud, is there?

11:04.456 --> 11:06.625
I can tell,
you know a thing or two.

11:06.625 --> 11:08.043
Join me in a walk?

11:08.043 --> 11:09.753
Now, that...

11:09.753 --> 11:10.837
Whoa, boy!

11:10.921 --> 11:13.715
...is Copper Jack,
my prize stallion.

11:13.799 --> 11:17.094
A stable boy walked a mare
past his stall this morning.

11:17.094 --> 11:19.179
Poor devil got a whiff,
and he hasn't been able

11:19.179 --> 11:21.890
- to calm himself since.
- Hmm. Your house, my goodness,

11:21.890 --> 11:24.976
it's even more stunning than
it looked in <i>Town & Country.</i>

11:25.060 --> 11:27.229
My great-grandfather
had it built in 1840.

11:27.229 --> 11:29.398
We throw on another wing
from time to time--

11:29.398 --> 11:31.066
birthdays, Hanukkah.

11:31.066 --> 11:33.068
Hmm, your family's
in the railroad business.

11:33.068 --> 11:36.071
Railroad, shipping, steel.
We're eyeing aviation.

11:36.071 --> 11:38.532
Innovation's key.
Stagnation is death.

11:38.532 --> 11:40.534
You're a businesswoman;
you know all this.

11:40.534 --> 11:42.786
Oh, yes, I am. I do.

11:42.786 --> 11:44.621
Mrs. Weissman,
I wanted to meet you,

11:44.621 --> 11:48.041
because your impressive match
for my lawyer's daughter

11:48.125 --> 11:49.876
did not escape my notice.

11:49.960 --> 11:51.711
Norma and Lorraine,
my two daughters,

11:51.795 --> 11:54.047
are 31 and 32 years old.

11:54.131 --> 11:55.132
Oh!

11:55.132 --> 11:57.175
- Uh, sorry.
- No, don't be.

11:57.259 --> 11:59.177
Their mother cries herself
to sleep every night

11:59.261 --> 12:00.887
wondering where she went wrong.

12:00.971 --> 12:02.806
Well, you've come
to the right place.

12:02.806 --> 12:04.641
Trees with a few more rings
on them

12:04.641 --> 12:06.601
happen to be
a specialty of mine.

12:06.685 --> 12:07.686
- Really?
- Mm-hmm.

12:07.686 --> 12:08.854
That's good to hear.

12:10.147 --> 12:11.815
I think we're gonna have
to give him Starlight

12:11.815 --> 12:13.233
just to calm him down.

12:13.233 --> 12:15.444
Horses are easy.

12:15.444 --> 12:17.237
You throw them together,
a little noise,

12:17.237 --> 12:20.490
maybe a stall door needs
repairing, and that's that.

12:20.574 --> 12:22.701
If only it were as simple
with daughters.

12:22.701 --> 12:25.495
- Tell me about them, your girls.
- Well...

12:25.579 --> 12:27.497
Norma has a penchant
for stable boys.

12:27.581 --> 12:29.708
- She's the Starlight of the family.
- I see.

12:29.708 --> 12:31.835
